We recommended that Management instruct:
a. The Municipal Accountant to maintain the Supplies Ledger Cards for each commodity or stock, record issuances of inventory, exert effort to reconcile non- moving balances, and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct/actual balances of the inventory in the financial statements;
b. The General Services Officer (GSO) to maintain stock cards for supplies which should always reconcile with the ledger cards of the accounting unit; consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI and submit the SSMI together with the original copy of the RIS to the Municipal Accountant to facilitate recognition of expenses in the books of accounts;
c. The Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain an updated and complete subsidiary and general ledgers containing the current and prior years transactions to aid in transaction tracking and reconciliation; and
d. The Inventory Committee to conduct the semestral count and prepare and submit the RPCI to the Audit Team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

a. Ensure the regular conduct of a complete physical inventory count of PPE, reconcile it with property and accounting records, and submit a comprehensive RPCPPE to the Audit Team, pursuant to requirements of Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I and Sections 6 and 7 of COA Circular 2015-008;
b. Instruct the Property Custodian and Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete, updated and properly accomplished PPELCs and Stock Cards for each class of PPE, listing therein the data as to its acquisition, description, custody, useful life and other necessary information;
c. Prepare and maintain general and subsidiary ledgers for all PPE accounts, indicating therein the beginning balances and transactions regularly; and
d. Avail of the one-time cleansing and follow the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 to establish PPE balances that are accurate and verifiable.

We recommended that the Management:
a) Formulate documented/written guidelines or uniform policy and procedures in the engagement of JO and consultant workers to ensure that the hiring process is systematic and include the standard qualifications based on the work to be assigned;
b) Execute contract of service specially for consultants that defines the technical knowledge and experience required, tasks and duties to be accomplished and its desired deliverables which are time bound;
c) Direct the HRMO together with the department heads/ immediate supervisors to ensure that job orders and consultants accurately reflect a quantified and accurate actual work performed and ensure that these are the actual deliverables stated in their contracts; and
d) Conduct regular assessment of the Manpower Complement of the LGU to determine whether the hiring of a permanent employee is more beneficial than the periodic hiring of job orders or consultants.

We recommended that the Management:
a. Instruct the Municpal Accountant to stop the practice of paying claims with improper and incomplete details/supporting papers and effect payments only if the required supporting papers are attached to the disbursement voucher;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to attach the checklist on documentation to all disbursement vouchers for processing as a helpful tool to ensure completeness of the required supporting papers and facilitate the submission of the lacking/deficient supporting documents noted.

We recommended that the Accounting Office:

Reconcile the loan amortizations deductions and remittances per employee;

Remit all loan amortizations deducted from the salaries of the employees in full and on time;

 Maintain individual subsidiary ledgers for payments of officials and employees as mandated to properly monitor the deductions and remittances made; 

 Reconcile the loan account with negative balances;

 Submit the lacking supporting documents on payment of employees’ loan amortization to PVB; and

 Assign to different personnel the duties of payroll preparation, processing of remittances and reconciliation.

We recommended the Management to:

 Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the difference of the unexpended balances reported in the Notes to Financial Statements and LDRRMF Utilization Report;

Transfer the reconciled unexpended balance to Trust Liabilities-MDRRMF account under the Trust Fund;

Prepare the Subsidiary Ledgers as required under  Section 5.1.12 of Circular No. 2012-002; and 

Submit the distribution lists.

We recommended that the Management:

Stop, or minimize the resort to cash advances and reimbursements for COVID-19 related expenses;

Strictly abide by the laws, rules and regulations on government procurement for emergency cases as mandated in GPBB Circular No. 01-2020;

Return the unutilized amount to the Bureau of Treasury; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to verify the completeness of attached supporting documents before payment is made; 

Require the supplier to deliver the undelivered items, else amount shall be paid by the signatories; and

Submit the lacking documents noted.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct the Property Custodian to maintain individual property card for all PPE owned by the LGU;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and updated PPELC;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory and submit the complete Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare an updated lapsing schedule.

We recommended that Management:
Send final demand letters to persons previously connected with the Municipality who still have unliquidated cash advances, otherwise, officials responsible for clearing said individuals from money accountability be held liable for the unsettled cash advances;
Require the immediate settlement of cash advances of officials who are still employed in the LGU;
Monitor the grant of cash advances and strict implementation of COA Circular No. 97-002 regarding the immediate liquidation thereof; and
Reclassify the amount of ₱850,175.41 to Other Receivable account and crediting the Due from Officers and Employees account by the same amount.

We recommended that the Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to validate and send confirmation letters to various creditors to validate/determine the exact amount of liability of the LGU concerned;
Ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to various claims prior to recording of liability account;
Reverse the entry made for those claims which were not pushed through for some reasons, such as cancellation of transaction or non-submission of complete documents; and
Exert efforts to locate the documents relative to the long outstanding payable and make the necessary adjusting entry, if there is any.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that Management:  

(1) require the concerned municipal officials and employees and Job Order Workers who are still in the service to settle immediately their outstanding cash advances, else deduct from their salaries the unliquidated cash advances; 


(2)  stop the granting of additional cash advances unless previous cash advances had been settled/liquidated;




(3)  send final demand letters to persons previously connected with the Municipality who still have unliquidated cash advances, otherwise, officials responsible for clearing said individuals from money accountability be held liable for the unsettled cash advances; 

(4) instruct the Municipal Accountant to monitor the grant of cash advances and enforce strictly the immediate liquidation thereof; and 

(5) request for authority to write-off the unliquidated cash advances especially those pertaining to deceased accountable officers.

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all PPE and prepare RCPPE with complete details; 



Require the Property Custodian Office to maintain individual property card for all PPE owned by the LGU;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELC to ensure proper monitoring;

Instruct the Accounting and Property Office to investigate and identify the noted differences between the Accounting records and RCPPE that may require adjustment/s; and

Undertake the necessary action/s for the disposal of the unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration and consequent depreciation in its value.

