We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
prepare the breakdown/details of the unutilized amount per year unexpended balances’ of LDRRMF and disclose the same in the Notes to Financial Statements; 

maintain subsidiary ledgers per year of transfer of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF; 

include all the information needed in the preparation of the MDRRMF Utilization Report; 

not to process transactions with inadequate documentations; 

follow the prescribed accounting guideline and entries in recording transactions charged to LDRRMF; and

prepare the necessary adjusting entries;



We further recommended that Management instruct the LDRRM Officer to:

observe proper safekeeping of supplies, tools and equipment under the custody of the MDRRM Office and maintain an updated inventory list on a regular basis; 

transfer the safekeeping and distribution of medicines under his custody to the Rural Health Unit (RHU);

submit the lacking documents required in the disbursement of LDRRMF under the QRF amounting to ₱320,000 to forestall the issuance of Notice of Suspension; and

stop the practice of procuring supplies and materials or services through reimbursement basis and ensure that the procurement process was in accordance with RA No. 9184; and



require the refund of the total amount of ₱15,466.17 to forestall the issuance of a Notice of Disallowance.

We recommended that Management:

a.) submit/ prepare a valid ordinance for the realignment/ reprogramming of available funds in order to support the obligations incurred/ paid to forestall the issuance of a Notice of Disallowance;
b.) require its key officials to have a close coordination in the budget preparation to be able to consider every aspect of the budget taking into consideration contractual obligations as in the case of the unfunded fire insurance and quarterly loan amortization;
 c.) reflect loan amortization and fire insurance should both be funded under EDF under separate Budget items; and
d.) strictly implement the budget to avoid disallowance of disbursements.

We recommended that Management direct:

the Municipal Accountant to submit promptly the monthly year-end Financial Statements and other reports/schedules for the General Fund Proper and other Funds for CY 2015 in accordance with the regulations;
appropriate remedial measures to ensure that year-end financial statements and required reports are submitted on time;
capacitate agency personnel through attendance to trainings and seminars to ensure an efficient and fast work outputs; and
strict adherence to the cited rules and regulations on the rendition of reports be enforced by the concerned officials in order not to incur penalty as provided in Section 122 (2) of PD No. 1445.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendation that Management: 

demand the immediate liquidation of cash advances of the concerned elective/municipal officials and employees and Job Order Workers  who are still in the service.  If still no liquidations are made, deduct from salaries long overdue cash advances;

stop the grant of additional cash advance for travel to all employees with unliquidated cash advances until such time that these are fully liquidated;

send final demand letters to persons previously connected with the LGU who still have unliquidated cash advances, otherwise, officials responsible for clearing said individuals from money accountability be held liable for the unsettled cash advances;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to monitor the grant of cash advances and enforce strictly the immediate liquidation thereof; and

request for authority to write-off the unliquidated cash advances especially those pertaining to deceased accountable officers.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
instruct the LDRRMO to prepare annually the LDRRMFIP for the programs using the prescribed format. Aside from the current appropriation for  30% allocation for QRF and 70% for disaster mitigation, prevention and preparedness with details as to projects and activities to be funded, it shall also include under a separate  caption, the list of projects; 
instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain separate registries as required in Section 5.1.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
require the Municipal Accountant to prepare breakdown/details of unutilized amount per activities charged to unexpended LDRRMF of previous years unexpended balances’ and disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements as prescribed in Section 5.1.16;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to follow the prescribed accounting guideline and entries in recording small items; and
refrain from charging to Calamity Fund expenditures that do not concern disaster risk management activities.

We recommended that Management: 

a.) require the Municipal Engineer and other concerned personnel to cause the preparation and attachment of above enumerated supporting documents so that no doubt can be casted against these disbursements;
b.) remind the Municipal Mayor, MBO, Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer to always affix their signatures to transactions which as to them are regular and valid and not otherwise objected to; 
c.) require the Municipal Accountant not to process claims when adequate documentation is not provided on the disbursement vouchers in accordance with COA Circular 2012-001; and
d.) direct the Municipal Treasurer to review at least the OBR and the DV for signatures before a check is made for the same.

We recommended that   Management:

direct the Municipal Assessor to prepare and submit to the Municipal Treasurer, on or before the thirty first (31st) day of December each year, an assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;
require the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible as basis to draw a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the debit to Real Property Tax Receivable/Special Education Tax Receivable and credit to Deferred Real Property Tax Income/Deferred Special Education Tax Income;
require the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team the list of Real Property Tax Receivable/Special Education Tax Receivable which should be the basis of recording of the RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred RPT and Deferred SET Income accounts for review and validation;
request for LGU Camarines Sur the details of collection of the RPT and SET amounting to ₱39,187.24, respectively;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to forward to the Office of the Municipal Accountant all documents attached to all remittances for reference in recording in the LGUs books; and
direct the submission of the list of tax delinquencies to the Office of the Sanguniang Bayan and request for their assistance to enforce collection of the uncollected delinquent taxes.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that Management: a) direct the concerned officers and employees to liquidate and  settle immediately their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports. Otherwise, withhold any money due from them. In addition, stop the pgrant of additional cash advance to all personnel with unliquidated cash advances until such time that these would be fully settled;

b.) strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring _controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances of cash advances by monitoring strictly the period of liquidated cash advances;

c.) send final demand letters to persons previously employed by the Municipality who still have --unliquidated - cash advances, otherwise, hold officials responsible for clearing said individuals from money accountability liable for the unseitled cash advances;

d.) prepare the request for authority to write-off the unliquidated cash advances of personnel who  were  already deceased which were carried over from the books of accounts of the Municipality;

e.) comply strictly with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; and

f) coordinate  with  the Commission on Elections to locate the present address of the absconding officer for sending of final demand letter,

